OH. You're describing a real problem called symmetry and you're completely right!
If weights start the same, they stay the same
If N4 and N5 start with identical weights:
N4 = ReLU(0.5×N1 + 0.5×N2)
N5 = ReLU(0.5×N1 + 0.5×N2)
They get the same gradient, update the same way, stay identical forever. They're literally the same neuron duplicated — total waste!

This is a real problem called "symmetry breaking"
And the solution is random initialization — weights start randomly different, so they break symmetry and each neuron drifts toward detecting something different during training.

But your deeper point still stands

"if the task only needs one combination, extra neurons are wasteful"

Yes! And this is exactly why:

Dropout randomly kills neurons during training — forces redundancy to not form
Regularization pushes unnecessary weights to zero
Network pruning literally removes redundant neurons after training


So the honest answer is
Fully connected layers are wasteful and redundant by design. We overparameterize on purpose:
Throw too many neurons at the problem
Let training kill off the useless ones
Keep what matters
It's brute force, not elegant. CNNs, attention etc. exist precisely because people got tired of this wastefulness and started building structure into the network instead.

Why initialize weight but not bias?
Weight initialization gives the next layer a number of gradients that all can learn as many patterns. Initializing weight is enough to break symmetry so bias initialization is not mandatory.


